1. What is critical IS research?

What is research in general?

  • âHow the world worksâ? (classic âscienceâ as in Wissenschaft / Naturwissenschaft)
  • âHow to make something newâ? (R&D â research & development)
  • âHow people think/behaveâ? (social sciences)

A critical perspective?

Critical IS studies aim at revealing, criticizing and explaining how the development and use of IS in organizations and society in the pursuit of efficiency, rationalization and progress also increase social control and domination, with potential detrimental consequences for some stakeholders and society as a whole. Being âcriticalâ in IS research also means subscribing to a much broader historical, social and political view of the IS discipline and the role of IS across all institutional levels of society. Critical research draws attention to the ways in which economic and managerial interests, ideologies and discourses, assisted by educational and research funding institutions, shape and construct IS research.

(Cecez-Kecmanovic, Klein, & Brooke, 2008, p. 123, emphasis added)

  • Revealing â âexplainingâ
  • Provoking â âcriticizingâ, âdraws attentionâ
Note
  • More about understanding (the extent of) the problem rather than already trying to develop the solution. In fact thereâs a concept in critical IS research called digital solutionism which critiques premature or naive solutions (Rowe, Ngwenyama, & Richet, 2020).
  • I think this is somewhat comparable to the concept of âcalling BSâ (Bergstrom & West, 2020; Christensen, KÃ¤rreman, & Rasche, 2019), e.g., âcalling BS on ChatGPTâ (Sundar & Liao, 2023).

Example: Schulzke (2014) on virtual worlds

While artificial worlds have enormous potential to facilitate communication, transcend spatial boundaries, promote free expression, and protect marginalized groups, the utopian promise of these worlds is undermined by their mirroring of real-world market systems, the exploitation of labor, and blurring the line between entertainment and work.

(Schulzke, 2014, p. 20)

Myers and Klein (2011)

Three elements of critical research (insight, critique, transformation)

Definitions taken from Myers & Klein (2011), p.Â 24; adapted from Alvesson & Deetz (2000).

  • Insight: âThis element is concerned with interpretation and gaining insight. Insight can be gained in various ways, e.g., using critical hermeneutics and the archaeology of knowledge, or the concepts of social reproduction via the mechanisms associated with symbolic capital.â

  • Critique: âThis element is concerned with critique, the genealogy of knowledge, and the social practices of control and reproduction. This element goes beyond interpretation to focus the researcher on the power structures that lie behind accepted interpretations.â

  • Transformation: âThis element is concerned with suggesting improvements to the conditions of human existence, existing social arrangements, and social theories. Theories are not the primary driver for changes, but potentially fallible lenses through which we see the world. The ultimate arbiters of the desirability of changes are those affected by them.â

Different kinds of action/rationality: Instrumental, strategic and communicative

Summary of the different kinds of action/rationality

Summary provided by Haj-Bolouri, Kruse Chandra, Iivari, & Flensburg (2016), pp.Â 8â9; adapted from (Habermas1984_Vol1?).

  • Instrumental: âAn actor follows technical rules of action and assesses the efficiency of an intervention into a complex of circumstances and events.â
  • Strategic: âAn actor follows the rules of rational choice and assesses the efficiency of influencing the decisions of rational opponent.â
  • Normatively Regulated: âAction refers to members of social groups whose actions are informed by commonly accepted norms and values.â
  • Dramaturgical: âAn actor evokes in his public a certain image, an impression of himself, by more or less purposefully disclosing his subjectivity.â
  • Communicative: âActors seek reach an understanding about the action situation in order to coordinate their action by way agreement.â
